erformance of “Apartment #9”—and it’s because of these vocal subtleties that it came to be called the saddest song ever written. Wynette similarly took on elements of camp and political critique in her artistry, demonstrating an underappreciated genius. Why Tammy Wynette Matters reveals a musician who doubled back on herself, her façade of earnestness cracked by a melodrama that weaponized femininity and upended feminist expectations, while scoring twenty number-one hits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCountry musicxHistory and criticism 0aCountry musicxHistory and criticism. 0aCountry musicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSingerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen country musicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen singerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aCountry Music, Domesticity, Sexuality, Mid Century, American South, Fame, Celebrity, Performance Studies, Tammy Wynette, George Jones, melodrama, soft politics, Reba McEntire, pain, camp, high femme, gender.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32464640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477327500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477327500/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK